Pod: The basic unit for running a containerized app.

Deployment: Manages and scales pods for you.

Service: Exposes pods to the network.

1. Install basic packages on all jetsons
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade -y
sudo apt-get install -y curl apt-transport-https ca-certificates software-properties-common

2. disable swap on all jetsons

sudo swapoff -a
sudo sed -i '/swap/d' /etc/fstab

3. Kubernetes component install on all jetsons
curl -s https://packages.cloud.google.com/apt/doc/apt-key.gpg | sudo apt-key add -

cat <<EOF | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list
deb http://apt.kubernetes.io/ kubernetes-xenial main
EOF

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y kubeadm kubelet kubectl
sudo apt-mark hold kubeadm kubelet kubectl

4. setup the master
sudo kubeadm init --pod-network-cidr=10.244.0.0/16

mkdir -p $HOME/.kube
sudo cp -i /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf $HOME/.kube/config
sudo chown $(id -u):$(id -g) $HOME/.kube/config

5. join the master (token is shown in the master in step 4)
sudo kubeadm join <master-ip>:6443 --token <token> --discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:<hash>

5a. if you cannot find the token or sha while running step4 on your master,use the following on master  to regenerate it then execute step 5 on workers again.
kubeadm token create --print-join-command


6. check on master

kubectl get nodes
kubectl get pods --all-namespaces

7. creating a pod

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: torch
spec:
  containers:
  - name: torchtest
    image: nvcr.io/nvidia/l4t-pytorch:r32.7.1-pth1.10-py3
    command: [ "/bin/bash", "-c", "--" ]
    args: [ "while true; do sleep 30; done;" ]

8. running the pod
kubectl apply -f test_k3s.yaml

9. connecting to the pod
kubectl exec -it torch -- python3

10.deleting a pod
kubectl delete pod torch

Advantages of Kubernetes
a. Automatically scales your applications up or down based on usage.
b.Spreads traffic evenly across pods to ensure reliability and performance
c.Automatically restarts failed containers.
d.Reschedules pods if a node goes down.
e.Replaces unresponsive containers or ones failing health checks
f. Deploy new versions of apps with zero downtime.
g.Roll back automatically if something breaks.
h.You define your desired state (via YAML/JSON), and Kubernetes maintains it
i.Pods run in isolated environments (namespaces).
j.Network policies control traffic between pods.
k.Secrets and config maps manage sensitive data securely
l. portability: an be run on any device
m.Massive community and tools support

example 1: how to use scale ups

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app-deployment
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-app
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-container
        image: nvidia.io.xxxx  # Replace with your image
        resources:
          requests:
            cpu: "100m"
            memory: "128Mi"
          limits:
            cpu: "200m"
            memory: "256Mi"
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80



apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: my-app-hpa
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: my-app-deployment
  minReplicas: 1
  maxReplicas: 10
  metrics:
  - type: Resource
    resource:
      name: cpu
      target:
        type: Utilization
        averageUtilization: 50

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f hpa.yaml

kubectl get hpa
kubectl describe hpa my-app-hpa

example 2: how to use services


# train_model is your training code, registered with your app.py. 
#all your code and app.py has to be a part of your container (copy in your Dockerfile,will be automatically build in your container) 

# app.py
from fastapi import FastAPI
from train import train_model

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/")
def root():
    return {"status": "API running"}

@app.post("/train")
def trigger_training():
    result = train_model()
    return {"message": result}


apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: pytorch-train-api
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: pytorch-train
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: pytorch-train
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: pytorch
        image: yourname/pytorch-train-api
        ports:
        - containerPort: 5000

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: pytorch-train-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: pytorch-train
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    port: 80
    targetPort: 5000
  type: NodePort

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f service.yaml

kubectl get svc pytorch-train-service
curl -X POST http://<node-ip>:<node-port>/train

or

curl -X POST http://<node-ip>:<node-port>/train \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"epochs": 10, "batch_size": 32, "learning_rate": 0.001}'
